Quintiles

Need to establish a set of genes from the entire Refseq annotations to focus on.
I used RefseqGRCh37.3 (ie the latest Refseq release for hg19)

RNAPII ChIP major peak occurs close to the promoter, so it seems to make most sense on using the promoter-proximal signal for sorting of genes. Otherwise one may sort by mean signal over the entire gene length.

Here I simply count 3 bins:
. -200 to TSS
. TSS to +200
. TSS+200 top +400

Data for this is from Pasha unscaled inputs and IPs counted using deeptools package
code not run only shown for documentation

#!/bin/sh

cd ~/faststorage/ClaudiaI/Pasha_Results/unscaled_wigs

mkdir "RefSeq_GRCh37.3_deeptools_summaries"

computeMatrix reference-point \
        -R "/home/schmidm/annotations/hg19/RefSeqGRCh37.3/ref_GRCh37.p5_top_level_genes.bed" \
        -S *_[I,P]*.bw \
        -out RefSeq_GRCh37.3_deeptools_summaries/RefSeqGRCh37.3_deeptools_promoter_summary.count \
        --binSize 200 --upstream 200 --downstream 400 \
        --averageTypeBins sum \
        --missingDataAsZero \
        --numberOfProcessors 4

load the promoter-proximal ChIP data

split inputs and ips and sum up all 3 bins

inputs <- dplyr::filter(cnts, ab=='Input') %>%
    dplyr::mutate(used_input = sample_name,
                  name = paste0(id, ':', chr, ':',start, '-', end)) %>%
    group_by(name, sample_name) %>%
    summarize(Input = sum(value)) %>%
    dplyr::rename(used_input=sample_name)

ips <- dplyr::filter(cnts, ab=='PolII') %>%
    dplyr::mutate(name = paste0(id, ':', chr, ':',start, '-', end)) %>%
    group_by(name, sample_name, used_input, siRNA, ab, run, main_run) %>%
    summarize(ChIP = sum(value))

put inputs next to IPs and get IP/input log2 ratio

(ChIP_rel_input <- left_join(ips, inputs) %>%
  mutate(Input = Input + 1,  #pseudount that should remove 0 count input outliers
         log2_ChIP_rel_Input = log2(ChIP/Input)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(desc(log2_ChIP_rel_Input)))

quintiles are simply defined as ranked log2 ChIP/Input average of all controls

(pc_ChIP_rel_input <- ChIP_rel_input %>%
  separate(name, c('gene_id', 'gene_name'), sep=':', extra='warn') %>%
  left_join(mRNA_genes, .) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(desc(mean_log2_ChIP_rel_Input)) %>%
  mutate(chip_rank = rank(mean_log2_ChIP_rel_Input),
         quintile = cut(chip_rank, 5, labels=c(5,4,3,2,1)),
         quintile = factor(quintile, levels=c('1','2','3','4','5'))))

Scaling

Load gene body signals

… using RefSeq_GRCh37.3 annotations & Pasha unscaled data

in this script every gene is split into 2 equal-sized bins each artificially scaled to 1000bp. According to deeptools it wont accept annotations, less than bin size, ie genes < 1000

collect counts in the files code not run only shown for documentation

#!/bin/sh

cd ~/faststorage/ClaudiaI/Pasha_Results/unscaled_wigs

mkdir "RefSeq_GRCh37.3_deeptools_summaries"

computeMatrix scale-regions \
        -R "/home/schmidm/annotations/hg19/RefSeqGRCh37.3/ref_GRCh37.p5_top_level_genes.bed" \
        -S *_[I,P]*.bw \
        -out RefSeq_GRCh37.3_deeptools_summaries/RefSeqGRCh37.3_deeptools_gene_halfs_summary.count \
        --regionBodyLength 2000 --binSize 1000 --upstream 0 --downstream 0 \
        --averageTypeBins mean \
        --missingDataAsZero \
        --numberOfProcessors 4

Load ChIP count tables:

add intergenic as 6th quintile to RefSeq annotations

(gene_body_cnts_quintiles_with_intergenic <- intergenic %>% 
  mutate(quintile = '6',
         gene_id=paste0(chr,':',start,'-',end),
         gene_name='intergenic') %>%

–> for background subtraction, quintile 5 is actually lower than intergenic (quintile 6). Possibly due to low RNAPII at unannotated but lowly transcribed regions.

–> signal from TSS-proximal half of gene body is higher for quintile1-3 but not for 4 and 5

–> can probably savely assume that subtracting “intergenic”" will be a too conservative background estimate and remove some low real signal, use quintile 5 instead…

Background correction

used as background estimate: mean quintile 5
–> assume that @ background input ~ ChIP –> to correct take the median for all libraries @ background and divide by that

to get how much input to subtract we need to assume input ~ chip in background ie: \[ scale\_factor_{input} = \frac{background\_mean_{ChIP}}{background\_mean_{input}} \]

and then: \[ scaled\_input = value_{input} * scale\_factor_{input} \]

ready to substract from ChIP values \[ BGsub\_ChIP = value_{ChIP} - scaled\_input \]

These BGsub_ChIP will then have on average value of 0 at background regions.

finally there will be some common scaling for the BGsub_ChIP \[ scaled\_BGsub\_ChIP = BGsub\_ChIP * \frac{1}{BGsub\_ChIP_{signal\_in\_normalization\_area}} \]

where signal in normalization area can be anything ie promoter peak height or gene body (-promoter) sum. see below.

use overall mean from all quintile5 ie background regions as 1st scaling factor …

background_means_input <- q5 %>%
  filter(ab == 'Input') %>%
  dplyr::rename(used_input = sample_name,
         mean_background_input = mean_value) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  dplyr::select(used_input, mean_background_input)

background_means_ip <- q5 %>%
  filter(ab=='PolII') %>%
  left_join(., chip_samples_table) %>%
  dplyr::rename(mean_background_chip = mean_value)

input_sf <- left_join(background_means_ip, background_means_input) %>%
  mutate(input_scale_factor = mean_background_chip / mean_background_input) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  dplyr::select(sample_name, used_input, input_scale_factor)
